            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Small work, in the form of 260 sayings of different contemplatives and spiritual travellers. It is divided into seven chapters; the first six on Vision, Hearing, the Word, Union, Knowledge and Love, with the seventh, longer, chapter dealing with a diversity of subjects. According to OY, based upon the Carullah 986 ms., it was composed in Baghdad, but in our reading of the note (see 47b) it is more likely that it was copied or collated there.</note>
               <note type="biblioComments">OY cites 27 mss., of which at least two can be considered as historic: Beyazid 3750 (c.782H) which was copied from IA’s original, and Carullah 286 (undated but early) which carries a note (see 47b) saying that it was copied and collated against a copy which had been read to the author; also Khalidiyya 892 (c.656H)</note>
